    "name": "Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis — hemolysis index drivers",
    "description": "Latin hypercube sampling over 12 uncertain inputs (blood viscosity ±8%, power-law exponent C ±15%, exposure-time integration step ±20%, inlet velocity profile shape ±10%, wall shear stress model coefficient ±12%, turbulence intensity ±25%, pump clearance gap ±5 µm, hematocrit ±3%, temperature ±2 °C, outlet pressure boundary ±5 mmHg, mesh density factor ±1 refinement level, and RBC fragility scalar ±18%) across 10,000 Monte Carlo draws. The power-law exponent C and RBC fragility scalar together account for 61% of the total variance in predicted hemolysis index; inlet velocity profile shape contributes a further 14%. These three inputs are flagged as the primary drivers of the wide 90% prediction interval (factor of 2.3 around the median HI) and are the subject of targeted experimental characterisation documented in the model-inputs and model-form credibility factors."
  },
